---
/**
 * GrowthPath — runtime growth path illustration section.
 * Shows the progression: In-Memory → SQLite → PostgreSQL → Cassandra.
 *
 * Placement: after the feature grid, before the consumption model section.
 * Acts as an architectural proof point for backend developers and
 * technical evaluators.
 */

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<section
  class="section section--alt growth-path"
  id="growth-path"
  aria-labelledby="growth-path-heading"
>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="growth-path__inner">

      <h2 class="growth-path__heading" id="growth-path-heading">
        Start local. Iterate with AI. Scale without re-engineering.
      </h2>

      <p class="growth-path__intro">
        Cyoda keeps the same model and API surface as you grow. Start in-memory
        for fast local development, AI-assisted engineering, and rapid iteration,
        then move to durable single-node, clustered, and enterprise-scale
        deployments when you need them.
      </p>

      <div class="growth-path__image-wrap">
        <img
          src={`${base}images/cyoda-growth-path.jpg`}
          alt="Cyoda growth path across in-memory, SQLite, PostgreSQL, and Cassandra runtime modes"
          width="1400"
          height="700"
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
          class="growth-path__image"
        />
      </div>

      <p class="growth-path__outro">
        You do not have to change the programming model as your requirements
        grow. Cyoda starts as a fast local runtime for developer and AI build
        loops, then scales through durable and distributed backends without
        changing the core model.
      </p>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>
